Vol / Page: 628
Edition:
Quote: <i>wash, washing stuff n. </i>alluvial soil from which gold is washed.
Notes:

Date: 28/1/1857
Source: Nelson Examiner and New Zealand Chronicle
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: The result of this sinking was not satisfactory, and contrary to most sinking in Australia, where the gold is not met with until a man gets down to what is called the washing stuff, generally only a few inches from the bottom.
Notes: written from Nelson, NZ

Date: 8/3/1882
Source: Southland Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 4
Edition:
Quote: Owing to the expensive mode of working adopted - entailing, as it does, the cost of the stripping of the over burden by pick and shovel, and the carriage of the washing stuff some distance to the sluice at the creek, the amount of gold saved (leaving the chance of striking other patches out of consideration) cannot, in my opinion, leave much profit.
Notes:
